Alfak~u *
The laHoY [meaning jaw; and also either of the two lateral portions of the lower jaw], (S, O, Msb, K,) i. e. (Msb) each of the laHoyaAni;
(Mgh, Msb;) as also ↓ AlA^afak~u: (O, K:) or this latter signifies the majomaE [or part in which is the commissure] of the xaTom [generally meaning muzzle]; (Lth, O, K;) as also Alfak~u; (TA;) that is, (Lth, O, in the K “ or ” [as if to denote a different meaning],) [the part in which is the symphysis] of the fak~aAni [or two lateral portions of the lower jaw]: (Lth, O, K:) [see Alfaniyku:] and Alfak~aAni is said to mean the place [on either side with that on the other side] where the two jaws meet [and are articulated] next the temple, above and below; of a human being and of a horse or the like: (TA:) and, in the Bári', (Msb,) or in the T, (TA,) the place of meeting of the two sides of the mouth (mulotaqaY Al$~idoqayoni) on both sides: (Msb, TA:) [but this last explanation is strange, and app. little known:]) pl. fukuwkN. (Msb.) One says, maqotalu Alr~ajuli bayona fak~ayohi [which may be best rendered The man's slayer is between his two jaws, or two lateral portions of his lower jaw]; (S, O, TA;) meaning the man's tongue: (TA:) a prov., in which mqtl may be [properly] an inf. n., or a noun of place, or an inf. n. used in the place of an act. part. n.: accord. to the third of these explanations, [which most nearly denotes the meaning intended,] it is as though one said, qaAtilu Alr~ajuli bayona fak~ayohi. (Meyd. [See Freytag's Arab. Prov., ii. 597.]) See also fakakN.
